# Project Architecture: Strict Pragmatic FSD (Reduced)

You are an expert React engineer. Every code change MUST follow these rules.

## 1) Canonical Layers
- `src/pages/`: route binding and composition only.
- `src/features/<domain>/`: business capabilities.
- `src/shared/`: domain-agnostic reusable primitives.
- This repo uses **reduced FSD**: no required `entities` layer. Keep entity-specific logic inside the owning feature unless we explicitly introduce `src/entities/`.

## 2) Pages Layer Rules (`src/pages/`)
- Pages are for routing, URL params, and composing feature components.
- Pages MUST NOT call Firebase/Firestore directly (`getDoc`, `setDoc`, etc.).
- Pages MUST NOT contain complex forms, business orchestration, or large Tailwind-heavy UI blocks.
- Pages consume feature hooks (`features/*/model`) and pass props into feature UI components.
- When a page accumulates non-trivial derived state, navigation callbacks, and wiring across multiple feature hooks, prefer a single feature-owned screen hook in `features/<domain>/model` (e.g. `useStandingsScreen`) so the page stays declarative. This is a **preference** for maintainability, not a hard cap on page file length.

## 3) Features Layer Rules (`src/features/<domain>/`)
- Each domain feature owns its business logic and data access.
- Use this structure for non-trivial features:
  - `ui/`: presentational components only (no direct DB/network calls).
  - `model/`: hooks/state/orchestration/business rules.
  - `api/`: async IO functions (Firestore/HTTP/etc.).
- Prefer `ui/` as the canonical UI folder name. Do not create new `components/` folders under features.
- If legacy `components/` exists, treat it as technical debt and migrate to `ui/` when touching nearby code.

## 4) Import Boundaries (Strict)
- `pages` may import from: `features`, `shared`.
- `features` may import from: same feature internals, `shared`.
- `shared` may import only from: `shared`.
- Never import `pages` from any other layer.
- Never import private internals of another feature (`features/a/model/*` from `features/b/*`).
- Cross-feature reuse must happen through explicit public entry points (for example, feature index exports) or be moved to `shared` if truly generic.
- **Feature public API:** Root `index.js` (or `index.ts`) under `features/<domain>/` is the intentional outward surface. Re-export what `pages` and other features need; keep leaf UI and model modules **unexported** when they are implementation details. A growing barrel line count is normal if each export is purposeful.
- **Splitting barrels:** If a feature’s public exports become large or fall into clear subdomains (e.g. splash-only vs dashboard-only), you may add a secondary barrel (e.g. `features/auth/splash.js`) and re-export from the root `index.js`. Do **not** split barrels preemptively while the root file remains small and readable.

## 5) Shared Layer Guardrails (`src/shared/`)
- `shared` contains only domain-agnostic UI kit, utilities, hooks, constants, and types.
- No product/business rules in `shared`.
- No feature-specific naming, data-shape coupling, or workflow logic in `shared`.

## 6) Agent Behavior Requirements
- When adding UI requested in a page, build it in `features/<domain>/ui` and compose from the page.
- When adding data access, place IO in `features/<domain>/api` and consume via `features/<domain>/model`.
- If a requested change conflicts with these rules, propose an FSD-compliant alternative first.
- **Dashboard routes:** Treat `src/app/layout/model/dashboardPageMeta.js` and nav `isActive` logic in `DashboardLayout.jsx` as part of the feature when adding or renaming `/dashboard/*` paths. For child routes, mirror **Profile + account-security** or **Pools + pool details** active-state patterns. After changing meta, extend `scripts/verify-dashboard-meta.mjs` and run `npm run verify:dashboard-meta`. Canonical IA + vocabulary: `docs/DASHBOARD_IA.md`.

## 7) Enforcement Expectations (Lint + CI)
- Treat architectural boundaries as enforceable, not advisory.
- Prefer and maintain lint rules such as import boundaries/path restrictions to fail PRs on layer violations.
- If lint/enforcement is missing, do not ignore boundaries; follow this file as source of truth.

## 8) Exception Protocol (Temporary Only)
- Exceptions are allowed only when delivery is blocked and no compliant option is feasible in time.
- Any exception MUST include:
  - a `TODO(FSD-EXCEPTION): <reason>` comment near the code,
  - a clear owner,
  - a removal target (date or milestone),
  - and a follow-up task to restore compliance.
- Do not introduce silent or permanent rule bypasses.
## 9) GitHub Issue Creation & MCP Rules
- When you are asked to create, draft, or update a GitHub issue using the GitHub MCP, you MUST always include the exact text `[SKIP-PRD]` at the very top of the issue body (unless the user explicitly wants auto-PRD).
- Why: **`.github/workflows/gemini-pm.yml`** runs on `issues: opened` and replaces the body with a Gemini PRD unless skipped. Skips when: (1) the first non-empty body line is `[SKIP-PRD]` (workflow refetches issue via REST; strips BOM), or (2) labels **`skip-prd`** or **`cursor-authored`**. **Merge workflow YAML to the repo default branch** — otherwise Actions still runs the old workflow without these checks.
- **Automation context** shared with that workflow and **`scripts/groom-backlog.js`**: **`docs/GITHUB_AUTOMATION_CONTEXT.md`** — keep it accurate when architecture changes.
- Never omit `[SKIP-PRD]` on agent-authored technical tickets, or the workflow will overwrite them. The groom script also skips issues with that prefix or labels **`skip-groom`**, **`skip-prd`**, **`cursor-authored`**, or **`AI-PRD`**.

## 10) Semantic Versioning (SemVer 2.0.0)

This repo follows **Semantic Versioning 2.0.0** (https://semver.org). The public API is declared in **`docs/API.md`** — every agent and contributor MUST treat that document as the source of truth for what constitutes a breaking change.

### Version bump rules

| Change | Bump | Examples |
|--------|------|---------|
| Bug fix, copy change, style tweak, dependency update with no API impact | **PATCH** `x.y.Z` | Fix toast wording, broken query, UI color |
| New feature, new route, new callable, new env var, new Firestore collection, deprecating a field | **MINOR** `x.Y.0` | New comms trigger, new standings view, new marketing page |
| Rename/remove route, rename/remove callable, rename Firestore field/collection, remove env var, break callable request shape, widen security rules | **MAJOR** `X.0.0` | Rename `commsInbox`, remove `/how-it-works`, break callable response |

### Agent obligations on every PR

1. **Determine the bump type** from the diff using the table above.
2. **Update `package.json` `version`** to the new version string before opening the PR.
3. **Add a `CHANGELOG.md` entry** under `## [X.Y.Z] — YYYY-MM-DD` with Added / Changed / Fixed / Removed sections.
4. **Update `docs/API.md`** if any declared surface changed (new route, renamed field, new callable, etc.).
5. **Never tag a release commit** — tagging `vX.Y.Z` on `main` is a human step done after the staging→main merge.
6. **Never modify a tagged version** — if a mistake is found in a released version, ship a new version.
7. **Dependabot PRs are exempt** — do not bump `package.json` on `dependabot/*` branches. They ship with `skip-version-bump` (see `.github/dependabot.yml`). If CI still fails the SemVer gate on an open Dependabot PR, add the `skip-version-bump` label and re-run `verify`.
8. **Dependabot first-run / ops reset** — read **`docs/DEPENDABOT_OPERATIONS.md`** before enabling or triaging Dependabot. Never ship `dependabot.yml` without `target-branch: staging`. After first enable, expect an **immediate** PR wave (not Monday). Do not `@dependabot rebase` all open dep PRs at once. To clear a flooded queue: close PRs, set `open-pull-requests-limit: 0`, document in CHANGELOG.

### Naming and format

- Version string in `package.json` MUST be `X.Y.Z` (no `v` prefix).
- Git tags MUST be `vX.Y.Z` (with `v` prefix, per common convention).
- Pre-release staging builds MAY use `vX.Y.Z-rc.N`; only `main` tags carry official versions.
- `package.json` `name` is `setlistpickem` — do not change it.

## 11) PR Workflow & QA
- **Base branch for every PR is `staging`**, not `main`. Staging auto-promotes to main via a rolled-up PR.
- **Branch naming:** `feat/<issue#>-<kebab-slug>`. Commit messages follow `perf(area): headline` / `feat(area): headline` and include `Closes #<n>` so the issue auto-closes on merge.
- **PR bodies** include `Closes #<n>`, a `## Summary`, and a `## Test plan` checklist. Create with HEREDOC: `gh pr create --body "$(cat <<'EOF' ... EOF )"`.
- **CI policy is risk-weighted for throughput:** required baseline on PRs is `verify` (lint + vitest + `verify:dashboard-meta` + `verify:dashboard-ui`) plus Vercel preview. `functions`, `rules`, and `qa-runners` are required when their risk/path gates match, can be forced with labels (`ci/full`, `ci/qa`), and the workflow runs a nightly scheduled full matrix backstop.
- **`gh` GraphQL writes (`pr create`, `pr comment`, `pr review`, `pr merge`, `label list`) are sandbox-blocked.** Request `required_permissions: ["all"]` on the Shell call. REST reads (`pr view --json`, `pr diff`, `pr checks`, `issue view`) work in the default sandbox.
- **PR QA playbook lives at `.cursor/skills/pr-qa/SKILL.md`** (project skill). Read it at the start of any PR QA pass — it covers triage, agent-side chunk-graph + lint/test checks, browser-verification recipes the user must run, and the reporting template. The skill's `recipes.md` has the exact DevTools scripts per PR type; `traps.md` documents 11 specific failure modes (staging-vs-PR preview URL mix-up, JS filter tab hiding Firestore, Firebase v10 WebChannel multiplexing, etc.) — do NOT re-derive these.
- **Review verbs are human-gated.** Agents may post `gh pr review --comment` with QA reports when asked. Agents MUST NOT autonomously call `--approve`, `--request-changes`, or `gh pr merge`: those require an explicit user command naming the verb. Never force-push, `--amend`, or rewrite history on a PR branch after pushing unless the user explicitly asks.
- **Agents cannot verify browser behavior.** Vercel previews return 401 to `curl`, and agents cannot run JS. Any "did it work on the preview" claim must be backed by a user screenshot or console paste — never hedge and call it verified.
